  Day5MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day6Dialog:
  - "People think armies arrive because of hatred, or belief, or great promises made
    to men who want to hear them. Most of the time they arrive because decisions
    were written down long before the first ship moved, and because refusing those
    decisions would have ended lives just as surely as any battle.\n\nI did not know
    this island before I was ordered to cross the sea. I knew my home, the sound
    of work in the morning, the way my child slept without knowing what waited beyond
    the door. Then suddenly I knew distances, numbers, supplies, and how easily one
    life can be exchanged for another without ever being named.\n\nPress F for more
    \u2192"
  - 'When you were brought into the camp, you were not the only small thing trying
    to survive here. A cat has been moving between the tents since the first days,
    staying close to where food is dropped, slipping away when boots grow heavy around
    it. No one ordered it to be fed, and no one bothered to stop it.


    The men
    inside the fort are defending what is theirs. That matters, and it should. Anyone
    would do the same if their home stood behind those walls. But the men outside
    did not choose whose land this would be, only that they would stand where they
    were told.


    War does not ask what kind of people it takes with it. It only
    asks whether they will move.'
  Day7FirstTimeDialog:
  - "You see this place and think it exists for fighting, but most of its work is
    quieter than that. It exists to endure waiting, hunger, heat, and the slow knowledge
    that tomorrow will look much like today, except with fewer people in it.\n\nEach
    morning, spaces appear where men slept the night before. No announcement follows.
    We step around those absences carefully, as if naming them might invite more.
    Food is divided again, tools are counted again, and work continues because stopping
    would mean thinking too clearly.\n\nPress F for more \u2192"
  - 'The cat still comes. Some days it eats well. Some days it does not appear at
    all. When it vanishes, no one asks where it has gone. There are enough disappearances
    already.


    Here, loss does not arrive loudly. It settles in, quietly enough
    that you only notice it once it has stayed.'
  Day7MetBeforeDialog:
  - "You see this place and think it exists for fighting, but most of its work is
    quieter than that. It exists to endure waiting, hunger, heat, and the slow knowledge
    that tomorrow will look much like today, except with fewer people in it.\n\nEach
    morning, spaces appear where men slept the night before. No announcement follows.
    We step around those absences carefully, as if naming them might invite more.
    Food is divided again, tools are counted again, and work continues because stopping
    would mean thinking too clearly.\n\nPress F for more \u2192"
  - 'The cat still comes. Some days it eats well. Some days it does not appear at
    all. When it vanishes, no one asks where it has gone. There are enough disappearances
    already.


    Here, loss does not arrive loudly. It settles in, quietly enough
    that you only notice it once it has stayed.'
  Day8FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Do not believe that death belongs only to the men behind the walls. That is
    something people say when they want the war to feel simpler than it is.\n\nWhen
    the guns answer each other, the ground does not care who is defending or who
    is attacking. Stone and iron tear through bodies without learning names first.
    The difference is only where the dead fall, and whether anyone will return to
    mark the place.\n\nPress F for more \u2192"
  - 'You see the fort every day. You do not see the pits behind the camp, where men
    who were alive in the morning are lowered into the earth by evening, wrapped
    quickly, because the work does not pause for mourning. By the next day, the ground
    looks the same again.


    Some of us have survived battles before this one.
    That does not make us stronger. It only means we know how little remains once
    a body stops moving, and how easily it could have been ours.'
  Day8MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Do not believe that death belongs only to the men behind the walls. That is
    something people say when they want the war to feel simpler than it is.\n\nWhen
    the guns answer each other, the ground does not care who is defending or who
    is attacking. Stone and iron tear through bodies without learning names first.
    The difference is only where the dead fall, and whether anyone will return to
    mark the place.\n\nPress F for more \u2192"
  - 'You see the fort every day. You do not see the pits behind the camp, where men
    who were alive in the morning are lowered into the earth by evening, wrapped
    quickly, because the work does not pause for mourning. By the next day, the ground
    looks the same again.


    Some of us have survived battles before this one.
    That does not make us stronger. It only means we know how little remains once
    a body stops moving, and how easily it could have been ours.'
  Day9FirstTimeDialog:
  - "You remind me of my son, though not because you are fearless or hopeful. You
    are neither. You watch carefully, as if understanding might protect you from
    what is happening around you.\n\nMy son will grow whether I return or not. If
    I die here, he will learn my face from stories told by people who loved me, and
    from silences where answers should have been. That is how war reaches into homes
    it never sees.\n\nPress F for more \u2192"
  - 'Every man here carries something like that with him, whether he speaks of it
    or not. We march with those faces in our thoughts, and we bury others while pretending
    we are not imagining our own names in their place.


    That is why I keep you
    close, and why I bring you food even when I should not. Not because it changes
    anything, and not because it makes me better than the men beside me, but because
    turning away would cost me something I am not willing to lose yet.'
  Day9MetBeforeDialog:
  - "You remind me of my son, though not because you are fearless or hopeful. You
    are neither. You watch carefully, as if understanding might protect you from
    what is happening around you.\n\nMy son will grow whether I return or not. If
    I die here, he will learn my face from stories told by people who loved me, and
    from silences where answers should have been. That is how war reaches into homes
    it never sees.\n\nPress F for more \u2192"
  - 'Every man here carries something like that with him, whether he speaks of it
    or not. We march with those faces in our thoughts, and we bury others while pretending
    we are not imagining our own names in their place.


    That is why I keep you
    close, and why I bring you food even when I should not. Not because it changes
    anything, and not because it makes me better than the men beside me, but because
    turning away would cost me something I am not willing to lose yet.'
  Day10FirstTimeDialog:
  - "You think survival means escaping this place, but survival is rarely that clean.
    Many men survive battles and never return to the people they were before. They
    carry the war with them, long after the noise has ended.\n\nThe cat survives
    because it does not belong anywhere. It eats when it can, sleeps where the ground
    is quieter, and leaves before danger finishes arriving. No one calls it brave,
    and no one blames it for staying alive.\n\nPress F for more \u2192"
  - 'Men are not allowed that freedom. The best we manage is smaller than that. A
    delayed order. A shared meal. A child kept out of sight long enough to matter.


    I
    cannot end this war. I cannot undo what has already happened. All I can do is
    decide, each day, whether I will add one more cruelty to the weight already pressing
    down on this place.


    If you live through this, remember what you saw here.
    Not who was right, and not who won, but how many small choices were made in the
    shadow of things too large to stop.


    That is as close to mercy as war allows.'
  Day10MetBeforeDialog:
  - "You think survival means escaping this place, but survival is rarely that clean.
